## A1 — Recognition Post (Day 1)

**Facebook — Recognition**

You have probably already started doing it. Checking the stove before you leave. Moving the sharp knives to a higher drawer. Testing the front door lock one more time.

You have not called it "dementia home safety." You have just been quietly making things less dangerous, one visit at a time.

This guide is a room-by-room approach to what you are already doing. Kitchen, bathroom, exits, bedroom. Practical changes, most of them inexpensive, that turn the scattered worries into a system.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**LinkedIn — Recognition**

For families caring for a parent with dementia at home, the safety concerns accumulate gradually. A burner left on. A fall in the bathroom. A door found open at 3 a.m.

This guide provides a structured, room-by-room approach to dementia home safety: kitchen hazards, bathroom modifications, wandering prevention, medication management, and the honest question of when home modifications are no longer enough.

Practical, GTA-specific, and written for the families making these decisions now.

