## A2 — Reframe Post (Days 3–5)

### Reframe 1: You are not overreacting

**Facebook — Reframe 1**

If you have been quietly moving things, locking things, checking things at your parent's home, you might feel like you are being too cautious. Too controlling. Too worried.

You are not.

If something in the house worries you, it is probably worth changing. That instinct you have been following? It is accurate. And the changes you make are what keeps your parent in that home longer.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**LinkedIn — Reframe 1**

Families often downplay their own safety concerns about a parent's home. They feel they are overreacting, being too cautious, or taking over.

In our experience, the opposite is more common. Families tend to underestimate the risks because the changes happen so gradually. By the time the concern is loud enough to name, the modifications are usually overdue.

If something in the house worries you, trust that instinct.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**Instagram — Reframe 1**

"Am I overreacting?"

No. You are not.

If something in the house worries you, it is probably worth changing. That instinct you have been following is accurate.

Link in bio for a room-by-room guide.

### Reframe 2: Wandering is not defiance

**Facebook — Reframe 2**

If your parent has started opening doors at odd hours, or you have found them outside without explanation, or you have woken at 3 a.m. to an empty house, it can feel like they are being difficult. Stubborn. Impossible.

They are not. Wandering is not defiance. It is a brain searching for something familiar in a world that is becoming less recognizable. The person is not trying to escape. They are looking for something that makes sense.

And there are practical things you can do: door chimes, camouflaged exits, removing the visual cues that signal "going outside."

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**LinkedIn — Reframe 2**

Wandering in dementia is frequently misinterpreted as willful non-compliance. It is not.

A person who wanders is a brain seeking familiarity and orientation in an environment that has become confusing. The behaviour is not purposeful in the way families often fear.

Practical interventions (door sensors, camouflaged exits, removing departure cues) are effective because they address the trigger without confrontation. This guide covers the full range of wandering prevention strategies.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**Instagram — Reframe 2**

Wandering is not defiance.

It is a brain searching for something familiar in a world that is becoming less recognizable.

They are not trying to escape. They are looking for something that makes sense.

Link in bio for practical prevention strategies.

### Reframe 3: Safety changes buy time

**Facebook — Reframe 3**

Some families resist making home modifications because it feels like admitting things are worse than they want to believe.

But here is what we see: the families who modify early are the families whose parents stay home longest. The grab bars, the stove auto-shutoffs, the nightlights, the locked cabinets. These changes are not signs that things have gotten bad. They are what keeps things manageable for longer.

You do not have to make the home perfectly safe before asking for help. Making it safer is often what buys the time to arrange it.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=facebook&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**LinkedIn — Reframe 3**

Early environmental modifications in dementia care are not an admission that things have deteriorated. They are what extends the window in which home-based care remains viable.

Families who modify the home proactively tend to reach the "crisis point" later, with more options and less urgency. The modifications buy time, and time is what allows families to plan rather than react.

This guide covers the practical changes, room by room, and names when those changes are no longer sufficient.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**Instagram — Reframe 3**

Safety changes are not signs that things have gotten bad.

They are what keeps things manageable longer.

The grab bars. The stove shut-offs. The nightlights. Each one buys time. And time is what lets you plan instead of react.

Link in bio.

