## A4 — Quiet Authority Post (Day 11–12)

**LinkedIn — Primary**

Home safety modifications for dementia are not a single conversation. They are an ongoing process that tracks with cognitive progression.

What works in early-stage (nightlights, medication lockboxes, stove timers) is different from what is needed in mid-stage (door sensors, camouflaged exits, full bathroom modifications). And there is a point at which no amount of modification is sufficient, and the honest answer is that 24-hour support is needed.

For professionals who work with families navigating this trajectory, here is a room-by-room guide that covers the full range, including the harder question at the end.

https://www.arcadiahomecare.ca/resources/dementia-memory-care/dementia-home-safety/?utm_source=linkedin&utm_medium=social&utm_campaign=dementia-home-safety

**LinkedIn — Link-optional alternative**

The families who call us about home care often started with home safety. A grab bar. A stove shut-off. A nightlight in the hallway.

Then the modifications accumulated, and the gap between what the modifications could handle and what the person actually needed grew wider. That gap is where our work begins.

If you are a professional recommending home modifications to families, the guide below covers what to suggest at each stage, and names when the modifications alone are no longer the answer.

